  "text": "## Node.js Child Process Command Injection Prevention\n\nThe Node.js child_process module implements comprehensive input validation and command injection prevention across JavaScript and C++ layers.\n\n### JavaScript Layer (lib/child_process.js)\n\nThe main entry point functions are:\n- **spawn()** (line 745): Core spawn function that normalizes arguments before spawning\n- **exec()** (line 231): Shell command execution wrapper\n- **execFile()** (line 323): Direct file execution\n- **fork()** (line 122): Process forking for Node.js modules\n\n**Critical Validation Functions:**\n\n1. **validateArgumentNullCheck()** (line 963-967): Checks if a string contains null bytes (\\u0000) and throws ERR_INVALID_ARG_VALUE if found. This prevents null-byte injection attacks where null bytes could terminate strings prematurely.\n\n2. **validateArgumentsNullCheck()** (line 970-974): Iterates through an array and validates each element using validateArgumentNullCheck. This ensures all command arguments and environment variables are free of null bytes.\n\n3. **normalizeSpawnArguments()** (line 538-709): The primary validation function that:\n   - Validates the file path with null-byte checking (line 540)\n   - Validates all command arguments with null-byte checking (line 556)\n   - Validates options.argv0, options.shell with null-byte checking (lines 597, 613)\n   - Validates all environment variable keys and values for null bytes (lines 691-692)\n   - Handles shell invocation with proper argument escaping\n   - Returns normalized options object with validated envPairs\n\nThese functions are called by:\n- fork() - validates execPath and execArgv (lines 142, 146)\n- normalizeExecArgs() - validates command parameter (line 190)\n- normalizeExecFileArgs() - validates argv0 option (line 292)\n- spawn() - calls normalizeSpawnArguments() (line 746)\n\n### Internal JavaScript Layer (lib/internal/child_process.js)\n\n**ChildProcess Class** (line 254-311):\n- Internal constructor that creates a Process handle from the C++ binding (line 266)\n- Sets up error handling and process exit callbacks\n- Provides the JavaScript interface to the native Process object\n\n**ChildProcess.prototype.spawn()** (line 354-488):\n- Validates the options object\n- Processes stdio configuration\n- Calls this._handle.spawn(options) to invoke the C++ ProcessWrap::Spawn (line 395)\n- Handles errors and sets up stdio streams\n\n### C++ Native Bindings\n\n**ProcessWrap Class** (src/process_wrap.cc, line 51-308):\n\n- **ProcessWrap::Spawn()** (line 153-312): The main C++ entry point that:\n  - Receives validated options from JavaScript\n  - Extracts file path from options (line 196-197)\n  - Rejects Windows batch files for security (lines 204-205)\n  - Processes command arguments array (lines 209-225)\n  - Processes environment variables (lines 237-251)\n  - Parses stdio configuration (line 254)\n  - Handles Windows-specific flags (lines 256-275)\n  - Calls uv_spawn() to launch the process (line 286)\n  - Cleans up allocated memory for args and env (lines 297-308)\n\n**SyncProcessRunner Class** (src/spawn_sync.cc, src/spawn_sync.h):\n\nHandles synchronous process spawning with additional safety checks:\n\n- **SyncProcessRunner::Spawn()** (line 376-385): Entry point that creates a runner and invokes Run()\n\n- **SyncProcessRunner::ParseOptions()** (line 752-866): Validates and parses options:\n  - Calls CopyJsString() for file path validation (line 764)\n  - Calls CopyJsStringArray() for args validation (line 779)\n  - Validates cwd and env arrays (lines 786, 794)\n  - Rejects Windows batch files (lines 773-774)\n  - Returns validation result\n\n- **SyncProcessRunner::CopyJsString()** (line 1005-1030): String copying with null termination:\n  - Converts V8 strings to UTF-8 C strings\n  - Allocates buffer including space for null terminator (line 1021)\n  - Writes string with explicit null termination (line 1026)\n  - Prevents buffer overruns\n\n- **SyncProcessRunner::CopyJsStringArray()** (line 1032-1098): Array copying:\n  - Validates input is an array (line 1041)\n  - Calculates total size needed for all strings\n  - Allocates single buffer for array and all string data\n  - Copies each string with explicit null termination (line 1090)\n  - Returns properly formatted argv/env array\n\n### Validation Chain\n\nThe complete validation chain for a spawn() call:\n\n1. **spawn()** in lib/child_process.js (line 745)\n   ↓\n2. **normalizeSpawnArguments()** (line 538)\n   - Validates file with validateArgumentNullCheck(file, 'file') (line 540)\n   - Validates args with validateArgumentsNullCheck(args, 'args') (line 556)\n   - Validates each env key and value (lines 691-692)\n   ↓\n3. **ChildProcess constructor** → new ChildProcess() (line 750)\n   ↓\n4. **child.spawn(options)** in lib/internal/child_process.js (line 354)\n   ↓\n5. **this._handle.spawn(options)** → calls C++ ProcessWrap::Spawn (line 395)\n   ↓\n6. **ProcessWrap::Spawn()** in src/process_wrap.cc (line 153)\n   - Receives pre-validated options from JavaScript\n   - Safely extracts and formats parameters\n   - Calls uv_spawn() with formatted options\n\nFor synchronous operations (spawnSync), validation occurs in:\n1. **spawnSync()** in lib/child_process.js (line 823)\n2. **normalizeSpawnArguments()** - same validation as async\n3. **spawn_sync.spawn()** - calls SyncProcessRunner::Spawn() (line 1106)\n4. **SyncProcessRunner::ParseOptions()** (line 752)\n5. **SyncProcessRunner::CopyJsString/Array()** - additional safety with explicit null termination\n\n### Security Features\n\n1. **Null-Byte Validation**: All strings are checked for null bytes (\\u0000) at the JavaScript layer, preventing null-byte injection attacks that could truncate command strings.\n\n2. **Windows Batch File Rejection**: Both ProcessWrap::Spawn and SyncProcessRunner reject batch files on Windows due to argument escaping vulnerabilities.\n\n3. **Explicit Null Termination**: The C++ layer explicitly null-terminates all strings to ensure proper string boundaries.\n\n4. **Early Validation**: JavaScript layer validates all inputs before passing to C++, reducing attack surface in native code.\n\n5. **Array Boundary Checking**: Both async and sync implementations properly allocate and terminate argv and env arrays with nullptr sentinels.\n\n6. **Permission Checks**: Both ProcessWrap::Spawn and SyncProcessRunner::Spawn include THROW_IF_INSUFFICIENT_PERMISSIONS checks for child process creation (process_wrap.cc line 158-159, spawn_sync.cc line 378-379)."
